Hey HN,<p>I had Claude build a CLI tool that analyzes GitHub forks to surface changes that haven&#x27;t been submitted as PRs.<p>The core idea is convergence: when multiple independent forks touch the same file and make the same change, that&#x27;s a strong signal something needs fixing upstream.<p>Example: I ran forkwatch against a Ruby API client library and found 11 independent forks all upgrading the same stale dependency. 4 of them made byte-for-byte identical changes to another file.<p>$ forkwatch analyze maximadeka&#x2F;convertkit-ruby<p>convertkit-ruby.gemspec (11 forks converge here)<p><pre><code>  WebinarGeek +1 -2 — Change gitspec faraday version
    -  spec.add_runtime_dependency &quot;faraday&quot;, &quot;~&gt; 1.0&quot;
    -  spec.add_runtime_dependency &quot;faraday_middleware&quot;, &quot;~&gt; 1.0&quot;
    +  spec.add_runtime_dependency &quot;faraday&quot;, &#x27;&gt;= 2.0&#x27;
  ...
</code></pre>
lib&#x2F;convertkit&#x2F;connection.rb (4 forks converge here)<p><pre><code>  Most common change pattern:
      require &quot;faraday&quot;
     -require &quot;faraday_middleware&quot;
      require &quot;json&quot;
  WebinarGeek, chaiandconversation, alexbndk, excid3
</code></pre>
It filters out noise (dependabot, lock files, CI config), groups forks by files changed, and deduplicates identical patches. There&#x27;s a --json flag for scripting&#x2F;AI and a --patch flag that outputs a unified diff you can pipe to git apply.<p>Uses the GitHub CLI for auth and one API call per fork. Written in Go.<p><a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;stympy&#x2F;forkwatch" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;stympy&#x2F;forkwatch</a>
